{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999615/1937120601/1163.xml":{"full_text":"F. D.\u2019s Program Checkmated\nas Congress Marks Time\nKaymond Clapper write* on Administration label* and policies. Page 19. 4\nAdsterial, \u201cA Cotten Pohey,\u201d Page 18. John T. Flynn diseuses houring.\nPage 19.\nBy United Press\nPresident Roosevelt returns to the Capital today to\nfind congressional rebels battering his special session\nprogram with a climactic attack on his farm bill and a\nformal move immediately to revise taxes to aid business.\nSenate and House leaders waited'\nRoosevelt's\ncounsel\nand possible\naction to untangle the legislative\njam. There was much uncertainty,\nhowever, on whether the President\nwould intervene forcefully as he has\non similar occasions in the past.\nWith only 15 days to go. the emer\ngency session called to enact a four\npoint program has so far done no\ntiling\nIt was unlikely that action\nwould be taken before Christmas on\nanything except the crop control\nmeasure which first must escape a\ndemand that it be returned to the\nSenate Agriculture Committee for re\nvision\nSEEKS TAX REVISION\nMeanwhile, Sen. William H King\nID Utah i announced he would intro\nduce legislation this afternoon for\ndrastic revision of the undistributed\nprots tax and the capital gains tax.\nThe Administration, successful in\nforcing the wages and hours bill out\nof the House Rules Committee after\nlong delay, was believed unlikely to\nact for revision quickly enough to get\na vote at the special session. partic\nularly in view of the new substitute\nproposed by the American Federation\nof Labor\nA. F of L. President Wil\nham Green, announcing his 40-cents\nan-hour and 40-hours-a-week meas\nure, disclosed demands which the\nrival Committee for Industrial Or\nganization has vigorously opposed\nand which may touch off a new\nlabor battle in Congress.\nABANDON PLANNING BILL\nAdministration hope of action at\nthe special session on the regional\nplanning and the government reor\nganisation bills have been abandoned.\nRoosevelt's request for reduction of\nscad expenditures has been virtually\npigeon-holed in both houses.\nCongressional troubles also ap\npeared likely to break out in the com\nmittee rooms as a result of announce\n\u25a0tent by Chairman Elbert D. Thom\nas (D Utah) that the Senate Educa\ntion and Labor Committee would\nmeet tomorrow to consider procedure\non a protest against appointment of\nHousing Administrator Nathan\nStraus.\nVANDENBERG FILES DATA\nThe committee has data tiled with\nit by Sen. Arthur H. Vandenberg,\n(R. Mich.) reportedly in connection\nwith Straus' real estate interests, and\nasking an inquiry as to his eligibility\nfor the post.\nencourage\nRoosevelt\u2019s efforts to\nbusiness revival at the special session\nhave not yet gone thru the required\nlegislative processes.\nSenate and\nHouse Banking Committees are ex\npeted to get amendments to the Fed\neral Housing Act to the floor this\nweek to push his drive for greater\nprivate housing investment.\n1000,000 Joss FLEDGED\nBoth Democrats and Republicans\nwere pressing demands for immediate\nRep. Emanuel Celler\ntax revision.\n(D., N Y announced that 72 cor\nporations had pledged re-employment\nof 1,000,000 men if the undistributed\nprofits and capital gains taxes were\nrepealed. He said a secret meeting\nof business men hear on Dec. 1 had\nresulted in the pledge.\nKing's amendments to a House\napproved income tax measure call for\na 50 per cent credit on profits before\npaying of capital gains taxes and for\na 40 per cent credit before payment\nof undistributed profits taxes In the\nlatter case, the corporation would pay\nnormal taxes on the entire profit.\nNew Jersey to Have\nState Labor Party\nBy United Press\nNEWARK. N. J., Dec 6-The New\nJersey convention of Labor's Non\nPartisan League made plans yesterday\nfor organization of a state labor party\nand adopted a resolution in favor of\nthe wages and hours bill now before\nCongress.\nIn line with the Committee for In\ndustrial Organization's recently de\nclared war against Mayor Frank\nHague of Jersey City, leader of the\nHudson County Democratic machine,\nthe convention condemned him and\n\"other anti-labor spokesmen.\u201d\nThirteen C. I. O. men were ar\nrested and others ejected from the\ncity Nov. 29 as the C. I. O. began an\norganization drive in Jersey City re\ngarded as a test of constitutionality\nof a city ordinance forbidding distri\nbution of circulars.\nThe convention was attended by\n368 delegates from 163 organizations\ncomposed of 150.000 persons. Repre\nsented were 110 affiliates of the\nC. I. O.. 34 of the American Federa\ntion of Labor, 14 with the Workers\nAlliance, and five with county non\npartisan leagues.\nI\nU. S. Begins Survey D.C. Airport Problem\nof District Health Subject to Parley\nThe U. 3. Public Health Service\ntoday begins its local health survey,\nwhich will cover hospitals, the local\nsituation on tuberculosis and other\ncommunicable diseases and high mor\ntality figures here.\nGallinger Hospital. subject of much\nrecent debate, will be studied. So will\nother hospitals where patients are\ncared for at public expense.\nDr Robert Oleson. Assistant Sur\ngeon General, will direct the activi\nties of a dozen experts from the na\ni tional health agency and from other\ncities.\n13 Are Held by Police\nin $1400 Liquor Theft\nThirteen men are being held in\nvarious precinct stations thruout the\ncity as a result of arrests by Wash\nington police and Federal Bureau of\nInvestigation agents in connection\nwith the theft of $1,400 worth of\nwhiskey last Monday.\nThe whiskey was reported stolen\nfrom a railroad car at the New Jer\nsey-av se freight yards.\nThree of those held are said to\nhave admitted participation in the\nrobbery and police are seeking a\nfourth. Others arrested include those\nsuspected of buying or selling the\nliquor.\nThe Whistle Simply Stuck\n8\u2014Workmen\nCLEVELAND.\nDec.\nbusied themselves today checking a'\nfactory whistle which disturbed Sun\nday morning sleepers.\nThe check\nwas suggested by police telephone\noperators who were kept busy telling\nirate persons there wasn't any fire,\nthat war hadn't been declared, that\nthe whistle had just stuck from 8 to\n6:30 a m.\nGen. Aiken Demands\nG.O.P.Oust Reaction\nBy United Press\nMONTPELIER, Vt., Dec. 6 Gov.\nGeorge D. Aiken of Vermont bid for\nleadership of the Republican Party\ntoday with an open letter to the\nnational committee demanding a\nparty purge and a constructive pro\ngram.\nThe governor proposed a nine-point\nprogram to avert a revolt within the,\nranks and a possible turning to a\nthird party. He said the party was\nin a \u201cnearly complete state of de\nmoralization.\u201d\nAiken, one of the few Republicans\nto win an office in the 1936 elections,\ndemanded that the party organiza- i\ntian be purged of \"its reactionary j\nand unfair element,\u201d that the \u201cyouth j\nof our nation\" be recognized and that\nthe party \u201cprepare immediately an\naffirmative program.\u201d\nThe 45-year-old governor said he\nsent the letter as \u201ctitular head of the\nRepublican Party in Vermont, and\nnot as governor of the state.\u201d The\nletter was released last night, less\nthan two weeks before the G. O. P.\nexecutive committee meets.\nTo rid the national committee of\nthe \u201cbaneful influence\u201d of southern\nmembers. Aiken suggested that each\ncommitteeman be allotted a vote pro\nportioned to the Republican vote in\nhis state cast for President in the\nlast national election.\nWashington's airport troubles will\nbe aired at a national conference of\nFederal, state, municipal and airline\nofficials, which opened today in the\nCommerce Department auditorium.\nThe problem of huge airliners and\nairports inadequate for their safe\nlandings and takeoffs exists nation\nally as well as locally and was to be\noutlined on a national scale at to\nday\u2019s opening session. Delegates were\nto state conditions existing in their\ncommunities.\nThe local dispute over Washington\nHoover Airport is only an exaggerat\ned example of the generl situation.\nThe conference will end tomorrow,\nafter acting upon recommendations\nto be submitted by a special com\nmittee whose members will be ap\npoined to study reports made to the\nparent group.\nHis Fine Record Didn\u2019t Help\nKANSAS CITY, Mo., Dec. 6\nCharles C. Shadwick helped fight\nhundreds of fires in his 33 years as\na member of the fire department.\nSeventy years old now, and on sick\nleave, Shadwick watched his home\nburn. He lived a mile outside of the\ncity limits. Neighbors,\nwho had\nturned in an alarm, were told the\nhouse was outside the department's\njurisdiction.\nOil Trial Resumes\nMADISON, Wis., Dec. 6\u2014The Gov\nernment today begins the 10th weeK\nof its trial of 16 major oil companies\non a charge of conspiring to fix the\nprice of gasoline in 10 midwestern\nThe trial, which may last\nstates.\nmore than three months, has been\ndelayed by continuous arguments\nover the Government\u2019s objections as\nto admisahle defense testimony.\nNews-Acme\nVICEROY OF ETHIOPIA\u2014The Duke of Aosta, new Italian\nviceroy of Ethiopia, succeeding Marshal Graziani. The Duke\nwears the typical North African costume and rides a camel\ninstead of a horse.\nMustn't Be Too Good\nWomen Are Warned\nBy CHARTER HESLEP\n\u201cMasculinity gone wild\u201d was the characterization of\nFascism in Italy and Naziism in Germany offered Wash\nington\u2019s Town Hall last night by Beatrice Forbes-Rob\nertson Hall, prominent feminist and former actress.\nHer spirited address, \u201cThe Women\u2019s 4\nMovement: Where Have We Moved?\"\nwas followed by discussion of topics\nwhich ranged from the District min\nimum wage law to the Christian vir\ntue of chastity.\nMrs. Hale, who was conspicuous in\nearly suffragette campaigns, believes\nlegislation pertaining to health, sani\ntation, working conditions and educa\ntion gets more consideration now be\ncause women have the vote.\nShe thinks women are nearer the\ngoal of \u2018\u2018equality of opportunity\" par\nticularly in the matter of a job. She\nremarked sarcastically\nthat\nthe\n\u201cfurther up the economic scale one\ngoes, the more violent becomes the\nmen's cry of \u2018disrupting the home.\u2019\nI never hear a man claim a poor\ncharwoman working thru the night is\nupsetting the applecart,\u201d she said,\nand brought applause.\nShe listed as liabilities of women\ntoday:\nDisappearance of the large family\nwhich she called the \u201cgreatest school\nof character-building,\" passing her\npermanent marriage in favor of a\n\u201cprogressive monogamy\u201d where chil\ndren often find themselves tangled in\na maze of step-mothers and step\nfathers; declining public approval of\nthe virtue of feminine chastity and a\nvanishing spirit of self-sacrifice.\nI\nNEW PAGAN VALUES\nReplacing these Christian concepts,\nMrs. Hale said, are a new set of\nValues that to her are essentially\nToday\u2019s heroines are the\npagan.\nHelen Wills Moodys, the famed avia\ni trixes, women in which the world\nsees physical prowess and perfection.\nTotalitarian states suppress the in\ndividual in favor of a \u201cnationalistic\ngod\u2014the state.\u201d This, Mrs. Hale con\ntends, is contrary to feminine psy\nchology and antagonistic to woman\u2019s\ninnermost self.\nIn this dressing up in uniforms, this\n\"cock-a-doodle-do\" stuff indulged in\nby the dictators she sees \u201cmasculin\nity gone wild.\u201d Asked why women of\nthese nations had raised no protest,\nshe said that German and Latin\nwomen were neither organized nor\nenfranchised when Fascist movements\nswept those countries.\nMrs. Hale thinks there should be a\nminimum of 50 women in the British\nParliament instead of the present 14.\nWhen Miss Jeanette Rankin, panel\nmember, asked if a 50-50 distribution\nwould not be desirable, the speaker\nsaid it would \u201cdepend on the kind of\nwomen elected.\u201d\nIsador Lubin, Commissioner of La\nbor Statistics, and Elsie Hill, leading\nfigure in the Woman\u2019s National Party,\nbrought up the local minimum wage\nlaw.\nThe latter declared it really was a\n\u201cwoman's minimum wage law,\u201d and\nMrs. Hale was emphatic in opposing\nspecial economic legislation for wom\nen.\nturn.\n\u201cTreat all alike,\u201d was her dic\nLubin countered that the law\nwould prevent exploitation of low\npaid salesgirls and to that extent it\nwas an advance.\nO. E. Baker, Agriculture Depart\nment economist, taking up the birth\nrate problem, and citing the rapid de\ncline in England (tho American-born,\nMrs. Hale has lived most of her life\nin London), asked if the English are\nalarmed.\nMrs. Hale replied that societies were\nbeing formed to combat the falling\nShe thinks the middle\nbirthrate.\nclasses use the plea of lack of money\nas an alibi for not raising families.\nHowever, she has faith in the \"will of\nthe Anglo-Saxon race to survive.'\n001-P0) <rr>w\nWE\u2019VE LOOKED\nEVERYWHERE AND\nHAVEN\u2019T FOUND\nMEANY MO\u2019\nP\n4\nar\nEVERYWHERE BUT\nSANTA\u2019S STABLES!\nGOSH! MAVBE HES\nOVER THERE, PLAN\n7) NING TO HARM\nTHE REINDEERS\nLETS GO!\n_ y\n053\na\n7*\n\u0964s\nW\nP\nWHATLUCK!TEy WON\u2019T\nSEE ME. ANP NOW IS\nMy CHANCE! I'VE HELD\nM BIGGEST DESTRUCTION\nPLAN TILL THE LAST/\nV\n3\nop\nu\n6\nTHANK GOODNESS, WELL, HE\u2019S\nTHE REINPEERS\nSOMEWHERE\ninc t\u2019SSvtta \u2014WOV\u2019t V IePl,\nARE ALL RIGHT. AND WE MUST\nMEANS\u2019 MO HASNT\nBEEN HERE.\nFIND HIM!\n7\n\n2\n29\ne\n\n1\nis\nMEANY MO\nREALLY\nMEAN\nENOUGHTO\nBLOW UP\nTHE\nPLACE\n2","height":"21072","width":"14400"}}
